# Topic 78: Data Skew ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

## Why?

Suppose you have **100 Million records**.

You partition by **Country**.

```text
India      → 90 Million Records
USA        → 5 Million Records
UK         → 3 Million Records
Australia  → 2 Million Records
```

Now Spark creates partitions.

```text
Executor 1 → India (90M)
Executor 2 → USA (5M)
Executor 3 → UK (3M)
Executor 4 → Australia (2M)
```

Three executors finish quickly.

One executor keeps running.

The entire job waits for **Executor 1**.

This is **Data Skew**.

---

## Concept

**Data Skew** occurs when data is distributed **unevenly across partitions**, causing some tasks to process much more data than others.

> **Simple Definition:** Uneven data distribution that creates slow tasks.

---

## Theory

A Spark job finishes only after **all tasks** complete.

If one partition is huge,

everyone waits.

This creates:

* Slow jobs
* Long-running stages
* Poor resource utilization

---

## Architecture

```text
Dataset
    │
Partition By Country
    │
    ▼

P1 → 90M
P2 → 5M
P3 → 3M
P4 → 2M

↓

One slow task
```

---

## How to Reduce Data Skew

* Better partition keys
* AQE (Adaptive Query Execution)
* Broadcast Join (when applicable)
* Salting (advanced technique)
* Repartitioning

---

## Interview Questions

### What is Data Skew?

Uneven distribution of data across partitions.

---

### Why is Data Skew bad?

One or more tasks take much longer than others, increasing total job time.

---

### How do you identify Data Skew?

Using **Spark UI**.

---

## Real-world Use

Large e-commerce datasets where one customer or country dominates the data.

---

## Common Mistakes

❌ Thinking adding more executors automatically fixes skew.

